= importizer
:toc:

Are you looking to convert your header-based C{plus}{plus} codebase to C{plus}{plus}20 modules, but
afraid that modularizing is too cumbersome? *importizer* is here to help.

And by modularization I don’t mean exposing a module interface and wrapping. headers. I mean
native modules a.k.a using modules internally.

*Note:* This project is currently going through a complete rewrite using Clang LibTooling to
replace Regex (pre-2.0.0). Much pre-2.0.0 things are gone, but releases and git history are
still preserved.

This project uses https://semver.org[semantic versioning].

== Why native C{plus}{plus} modules?

* *Improved compilation time:* Modules don’t need to be recompiled every time it is imported,
unlike headers.
* *Improved encapsulation:* Modules allow you to choose what is exposed to users (exported), no
need to hide stuff with a `detail` namespace. Includes and macros from a module will only stay
in that module.
* https://arewemodulesyet.org

== Prebuilt binaries

Importizer provides pre-compiled binaries for major operating systems. Necessary shared
libraries are bundled directly in the distribution archive.

[%autowidth]
|===
| |Linux |macOS |Windows

|Architecture
3+^|x64, arm64

|Minimum OS |None |macOS 15{plus} |Windows 10{plus}
|Format (debug) |tzst(bin {plus} .so) |tzst(bin {plus} .dylib) |tzst(bin {plus} .dll)

|Format (release)
3+^|zst(bin)
|===

*Downloads:*

* *Stable release:* Download optimized release builds from the
https://github.com/msqr1/importizer/releases[releases page].
* *Bleeding edge (debug):* Download unoptimized builds from the
https://github.com/msqr1/importizer/releases/tag/continuous[continuous tag]. Useful for testing
latest features or reporting bugs.

== Configuration & usage

Importizer is primarily driven by a TOML configuration file, complemented by a few command-line
arguments.

=== Command-line interface (CLI)

By default, running `importizer` looks for an `importizer.toml` file in the current working
directory. You can override this by passing the path as a positional argument:
`importizer` `path/to/config.toml`.

[%autowidth]
|===
|Option |Description
|-h, --help |Print help information and exit.
|-v, --version |Print version information and exit.
|-o, --outDir |Override the output directory specified in the config file.
|-r, --raw |Disable ANSI styling in logs (`always` or `never`). Defaults to `always` if no
value is provided. Can also be toggled via the `RAW` environment variable.
|===

=== Configuration file (TOML)

All relative paths defined in the configuration file are resolved relative to the configuration
file’s location, *not* the current working directory.

[%autowidth]
|===
|Option |Type |Description
|`inDir` |String |*Required.* The directory containing the source code to process.
|`outDir` |String |*Required* (unless provided via CLI). The directory for the modularized
output.
|`compilationDb` |String |*Highly Recommended.* Path to a `compile_commands.json` compilation
database to provide accurate AST parsing context.
|===

==== Bootstrap mode

For projects without a JSON compilation database, Importizer can attempt to imitate one using
the `[bootstrap]` table. Note: If `compilationDb` is specified, the `bootstrap` table is
ignored.

[%autowidth]
|===
|Option |Type |Default |Description
|`hdrExts` |String Array |`["h","hh","hpp","hxx",""]` |Header file extensions used in the
project.
|`srcExts` |String Array |`["cc","cpp","cxx","c{plus}{plus}","C"]` |Source file extensions used
in the project.
|`includePaths` |String Array |`[]` |Include paths to search during AST parsing.
|===

=== Example config file

[source,toml]
----
inDir = "src"
outDir = "modular_src"
# compilationDb = "build/compile_commands.json"

[bootstrap]
includePaths = ["include", "third_party/libs"]
----

== Developing

=== Build environment
Importizer heavily relies on Clang LibTooling. To save developers from compiling it and speed up builds, there's prebuilt ones.

Because C++ ABIs and LLVM bitcode formats change drastically between compilers and patch versions:

* **Skipping building LibTooling:** If you use the exact compiler toolchain in the table below, the
prebuilt LibTooling will link seamlessly.
* **Building from source entirely:** You are free to use other compiler toolchains (GCC, MSVC, Apple Clang, another Clang), but you will have to rebuild LibTooling with that toolchain.

[%autowidth]
|===
| |Linux |MacOS |Windows

|Build system
3+^|CMake 3.31.5{plus}

|Generator
|Ninja^1^, Makefile
|Ninja^1^
|Ninja^1^

|Compiler
|Clang 18.1.8
|Clang 18.1.8 (Homebrew)
|Clang 20.1.x^2^

|Backend
|`build-essential`
|Xcode SDK (`SDKROOT`)
|Visual Studio or Build Tools^3^
|===

. Highly recommended for faster builds.
. `20.1.8` on x64, `20.1.6` on ARM64.
. Used strictly to provide the Windows SDK.

Setup your environment (check architecture, compiler & backend to PATH) by running `. script/setup-env/[OS]`. Things to note:

* Windows
** For now, only Visual Studio is checked and not Build Tools because of `vswhere`.
** There's an optional argument `llvmPrefix` to change the directory (default `C:/Program Files/LLVM`) to look for LLVM. It can take the special value of `:bundled` that tells the script to look for the LLVM bundled within Visual Studio or Build Tools.

=== Dependency linkage

Because Importizer relies heavily on Clang LibTooling and LLVM, the resulting binary linkage
varies by operating system

[%autowidth]
|===
| |Linux |MacOS |Windows

|LibTooling
|Dynamic^1^
2+^|Static

|Other 3rd-party
3+^|Static

|C++ Standard Library |Static |Dynamic^2^ |Static
|C Standard Library |Dynamic^3^ |Dynamic^2^ |Dynamic^4^
|===

. Package manager doesn’t offer static build, pending self-built LLVM.
. Dynamic with stable ABI guaranteed by macOS (libSystem), we can treat as if static.
. Dynamic glibc, pending switch to a static C Standard Library (musl, LLVM libc).
. Dynamic with stable ABI guaranteed by Windows (UCRT), we can treat as if static.

=== Building from source

Standard CMake build process. To clone and build the release executable:

[source,bash]
----
git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/msqr1/importizer
cd importizer

# Configure the project
cmake -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release

# Build using all available cores
cmake --build build --config Release -j $(cmake -P scripts/Nproc.cmake)
----

* The compiled executable will be located in the `build` directory

=== Running tests

Tests are not enabled by default, but can be toggled via the `BUILD_TESTING` CMake option.

[source,bash]
----
# Ensure tests are configured (Debug mode recommended for testing)
cmake -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug -DBUILD_TESTING=ON
cmake --build build --config Debug -j $(cmake -P scripts/Nproc.cmake)

# Run the test suite using all available cores
ctest --test-dir build/tests --output-on-failure --progress --schedule-random -j \
  $(cmake -P scripts/Nproc.cmake)
----

=== Adding new tests

Importizer uses a custom directory-based test harness (located in `src/run-test`). To add a new
test case:

. Create a new directory under `tests/` with a descriptive name (e.g., `tests/my-new-feature/`).
. Add a `Config.toml` file inside this directory to configure the importizer run.
. Add a `RefCli.txt` file containing the expected CLI output.
. *(Optional)* Create a `in/` subdirectory containing the input files (C{plus}{plus}
header-based code).
. *(Optional)* Create a `ref/` subdirectory containing the expected output files. The test driver will automatically compare the actual output directory against this reference directory. Don’t add this when expecting an error.

The CMake script dynamically globs the `tests/` folder, so your new test will be automatically picked up on the next `cmake` `-B` `build` run.

== Contributing

Thank you for helping to improve Importizer! The coding standard is a spin-off of LLVM's, see below:

=== Naming conventions

* *C{plus}{plus}, CMake, and scripts variables/functions:* `camelCase`
* *C{plus}{plus} classes, types, & files:* `PascalCase` (e.g., `MyClass.cc`)
* *Executables & directories:* `kebab-case` (e.g., `run-test/`)
* *CMake & scripts external variables:* `ALL_CAPS_SNAKE_CASE`

=== C{plus}{plus} code style

* Follow the LLVM coding style.
* 100-column line limit, which is automatically handled by `.clang_format`.
* Use `std::string_view` over `const char*`, and `std::array`/`std::vector` over C-style
arrays.
* Use angled brackets (`#include <header.h>`) for external/third-party headers.
* The C{plus}{plus} file containing `main()` for any executable must be named `Driver.cc`.
* Maintain the exact same ordering of options in the Options section and parsing logic in
`getOpts`.

=== Error eandling (without exceptions)

Like LLVM, Importizer *does not use C{plus}{plus} exceptions*.

* *Return Values:* Mark fallible functions with `[nodiscard]` and return `bool` (or a type implicitly convertible to `bool`).
* *Logging:* Functions must handle logging their own errors and should be marked `noexcept`.
* *System Errors:* Mark branches handling system-level errors (e.g., `fseek` or `ftell`
failures) with `[unlikely]`. Do not use this for standard user input validation.
* *Early Exits:* For an errorless early exit (e.g., the user requested `--help` or `--version`),
return `std::optional<bool>` with `std::nullopt` to signal to the caller that execution should halt successfully without an error code.

=== Build system (CMake)

* Always place `common-config` as the *first* item in your `target_link_libraries` list.
* Only use generator expressions for build-time conditionals, not for configure-time conditionals.
* Check a compiler/linker flag if it's not guaranteed to be available (e.g., `-fsanitize=address`)
* `3rd-party` directory must only contain 3rd-party libraries used by the project
* Use `target\_*_*` to add flags for this project, and `add\_*_*` to add for this and all dependencies. Note https://gitlab.kitware.com/cmake/cmake/-/work_items/27854[this issue].

=== Checklists

For a new release:

. Update importizer's version string in:
** `.github/workflows/Release.yml`
** `ChangeLog.asc` (delete "in progress")
** `src/importizer/Opts.cc`
** `CMakeLists.txt`
. Run the Tag Release workflow, it will:
** Check if the last commit built and tested successfully (in Debug mode).
** Check if LibTooling binaries are
** Build and test on its own (in Release mode).
** Tag the new release.

When bumping LibTooling version:

. Tag a new release with:
** Title: `libtooling-[v]`
** Tag: `libtooling-[v]`
** Description: `LibTooling [v] for developers and CI.`
** Pre-release
. Update the version string & hash in `scripts/EnsureLibtooling.cmake`

When pushing, ensure permission of `.sh` files in `scripts/` is set to executable. You can use the provided git hook to do this for you:
[source,bash]
----
git config core.hooksPath .githooks
----
